ars about child abuse. Drawing on feminist, queer, and poststructural theories, the authors argue for the restoration of pleasure as a goal of early childhood education.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aChild developmentxUnited States. 0aChild developmentzUnited States. 0aChild psychologyxUnited States. 0aChild psychologyzUnited States. 0aEarly childhood educationxMoral and ethical aspectsxUnited StatesxUnited StatesxUSA. 0aEarly childhood educationxMoral and ethical aspectszUnited States. 0aEarly childhood educationxSocial aspectsxUnited States. 0aEarly childhood educationxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aPleasurexMoral and ethical aspectsxUnited States. 0aPleasurexMoral and ethical aspectszUnited States. 0aSex (Psychology). 0aTeacher-student relationshipsxUnited States. 0aTeacher-student relationshipszUnited States. 7aEDUCATION / Elementary.2bisacsh1 aTobin, Joseph J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066772108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013z978311053799440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300146493423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300146493.jpg  a978-3-11-053799-4  Yale University Press eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066772-1  YUP eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles